---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro'
import Header from '../components/Header.astro'
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro'
import DownloadButton from '../components/DownloadButton.astro'
import NewsletterInlineWrapper from '../components/NewsletterInlineWrapper.astro'
---

<Layout
    title="Features - Cmdr"
    description="What Cmdr can do today and what's coming next. Full-disk indexing, on-device AI, keyboard-first navigation, and more."
>
    <Header />
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 pt-32 pb-24">
        <!-- Hero -->
        <header class="mb-16 text-center">
            <h1 class="mb-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-[var(--color-text-primary)] md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl">
                What Cmdr can do
            </h1>
            <p class="text-lg text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                Shipped features you can use today, and what's coming next.
            </p>
        </header>

        <!-- Shipped features -->
        <div class="space-y-12">
            <!-- Full-disk index -->
            <section
                id="full-disk-index"
                class="scroll-mt-24 rounded-2xl border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-8"
            >
                <div class="mb-1 flex items-center gap-3">
                    <img src="/icons/database.svg" alt="" class="size-8" />
                    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--color-text-primary)]">Live full-disk index</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                    <p>
                        Cmdr indexes your entire drive in ~4 minutes. After that, it stays current forever through
                        real-time file system events (FSEvents on macOS, inotify on Linux). No re-scans, no cron jobs.
                        Restart the app and the index picks up right where it left off.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The index tracks every file and directory with recursive size aggregates. That means you see
                        folder sizes right in the file listing, no waiting. The whole thing runs on a single-writer
                        SQLite architecture with WAL mode, so reads never block the UI.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        On top of that, Cmdr runs a background verifier: every time you navigate to a directory, it
                        quietly diffs the index against disk and fixes any drift. Belt and suspenders.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Private LLM -->
            <section
                id="private-llm"
                class="scroll-mt-24 rounded-2xl border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-8"
            >
                <div class="mb-1 flex items-center gap-3">
                    <img src="/icons/sparkles.svg" alt="" class="size-8" />
                    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--color-text-primary)]">Private LLM included</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                    <p>
                        Cmdr ships with a 3B parameter language model that runs entirely on your Mac. No internet
                        connection needed, no data leaves your machine. It powers features like folder name suggestions
                        and smart search. The model is small (it's a 3B, not GPT-4), but it's fully private.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If you want more capable AI, connect your own API key for OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, Groq, or
                        any OpenAI-compatible endpoint. Local models hosted outside Cmdr (like Ollama) work too. The
                        settings panel auto-detects available models from your provider and lets you pick one.
                    </p>
                    <p>The on-device model requires Apple Silicon. Cloud providers work on any hardware.</p>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Speed -->
            <section
                id="speed"
                class="scroll-mt-24 rounded-2xl border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-8"
            >
                <div class="mb-1 flex items-center gap-3">
                    <img src="/icons/rocket.svg" alt="" class="size-8" />
                    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--color-text-primary)]">Blazing fast</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                    <p>
                        Built in Rust with a Tauri frontend. Cmdr opens a 100,000-file folder in ~4 seconds with icons,
                        sizes, and dates. Try that in Finder.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Large directories stream in progressively: you see the first files immediately while the rest
                        load in the background. The UI stays responsive throughout (Tab works, Escape cancels). Sorting
                        50,000 entries takes ~15ms.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The file listing uses on-demand fetching: only visible rows get sent over the IPC bridge. Scroll
                        through a million files without breaking a sweat.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Keyboard-first -->
            <section
                id="keyboard-first"
                class="scroll-mt-24 rounded-2xl border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-8"
            >
                <div class="mb-1 flex items-center gap-3">
                    <img src="/icons/keyboard.svg" alt="" class="size-8" />
                    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--color-text-primary)]">Keyboard-first</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                    <p>
                        Two panes, tabs, a command palette, and fully customizable keyboard shortcuts. Navigate, select,
                        copy, move, rename, create files and folders, all without touching the mouse.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Shortcuts are scope-aware: the same key combo can do different things in different contexts
                        (file list vs. settings window vs. search dialog). Conflict detection warns you when scopes
                        overlap. Customize any shortcut, and menu accelerators update automatically.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Three density modes (compact, comfortable, spacious) let you fit more files on screen or give
                        yourself breathing room. The whole UI adapts.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </section>
        </div>

        <!-- Coming next separator -->
        <p class="my-12 text-center text-sm font-medium tracking-wide text-[var(--color-text-tertiary)] uppercase">
            Coming next
        </p>

        <!-- Upcoming features -->
        <div class="space-y-12">
            <!-- Smart search -->
            <section
                id="smart-search"
                class="scroll-mt-24 rounded-2xl border border-[var(--color-accent)]/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-[var(--color-surface)] to-[var(--color-accent)]/5 p-8"
            >
                <div class="mb-1 flex items-center justify-between">
                    <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
                        <img src="/icons/search.svg" alt="" class="size-8" />
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--color-text-primary)]">Smart search</h2>
                    </div>
                    <a
                        href="/roadmap"
                        class="rounded-full bg-[var(--color-accent)]/20 px-2.5 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-[var(--color-accent-text)] transition-colors hover:bg-[var(--color-accent)]/30"
                    >
                        Works but early stage
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                    <p>
                        Find files by describing them in plain language: "that PDF contract from last month" or
                        "screenshots with error messages." The LLM classifies your intent into structured filters (file
                        type, time range, size, scope), and Rust does the actual search deterministically.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The search runs against the in-memory index (~5 million entries), scanned in parallel with
                        rayon. Sub-second results for most queries. The AI layer uses a key-value line format instead of
                        JSON, because even small LLMs can produce key-value pairs reliably (JSON generation fails ~13%
                        of the time on 2B models).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This feature works today but it's still rough around the edges. We're improving accuracy and
                        adding more filter types.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- AI rename -->
            <section
                id="ai-rename"
                class="scroll-mt-24 rounded-2xl border border-[var(--color-accent)]/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-[var(--color-surface)] to-[var(--color-accent)]/5 p-8"
            >
                <div class="mb-1 flex items-center justify-between">
                    <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
                        <img src="/icons/brain.svg" alt="" class="size-8" />
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--color-text-primary)]">Natural language rename</h2>
                    </div>
                    <a
                        href="/roadmap"
                        class="rounded-full bg-[var(--color-accent)]/20 px-2.5 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-[var(--color-accent-text)] transition-colors hover:bg-[var(--color-accent)]/30"
                    >
                        Coming soon
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                    <p>
                        Select files, type "make these lowercase and add date prefix," and watch it happen. No regex, no
                        scripts, no renaming tools with 47 checkboxes.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Cmdr shows you a preview of all renames before applying them. If something looks off, tweak your
                        instruction and try again. Works with the on-device model or your cloud provider.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- AI batch -->
            <section
                id="ai-batch"
                class="scroll-mt-24 rounded-2xl border border-[var(--color-accent)]/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-[var(--color-surface)] to-[var(--color-accent)]/5 p-8"
            >
                <div class="mb-1 flex items-center justify-between">
                    <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
                        <img src="/icons/zap.svg" alt="" class="size-8" />
                        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[var(--color-text-primary)]">AI batch operations</h2>
                    </div>
                    <a
                        href="/roadmap"
                        class="rounded-full bg-[var(--color-accent)]/20 px-2.5 py-1 text-xs font-medium text-[var(--color-accent-text)] transition-colors hover:bg-[var(--color-accent)]/30"
                    >
                        Coming soon
                    </a>
                </div>
                <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                    <p>
                        Organize hundreds of files with a single command. "Sort these into folders by project name."
                        "Move all receipts to ~/Documents/Receipts and rename them by date." Describe the outcome you
                        want, and Cmdr figures out the steps.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Like AI rename, you'll see a full preview before anything moves. Batch operations are the big
                        one we're working toward. The file index, AI pipeline, and file operations infrastructure are
                        all in place. Now it's about connecting them.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </section>
        </div>

        <!-- Download CTA -->
        <div class="mt-20 text-center">
            <h2 class="mb-4 text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--color-text-primary)]">
                Wanna see it for yourself? Get Cmdr now.
            </h2>
            <p class="mb-8 text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]">
                Free forever for personal use. No signup, no trial period.
            </p>
            <div class="mx-auto max-w-xs">
                <DownloadButton variant="card" class="w-full" />
            </div>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-[var(--color-text-tertiary)]">macOS only · Source-available (BSL 1.1)</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Newsletter -->
        <div class="mt-16">
            <NewsletterInlineWrapper label="Get notified about new features and releases:" />
        </div>
    </main>
    <Footer />
</Layout>
